{"title": "There Are No Tents", "content": "In many a Role-Playing Game, the Player Character can't keep Walking the Earth and deal with Random Encounters forever due to running low on Hit Points or Mana Meter. Since a Healing Potion is best saved for emergencies, the easiest (and cheapest) way to recover is to visit a Trauma Inn and rest for the night (at any time of the day, since usually the game barely if at all keeps track of the passage of time).\n\nUnfortunately, the hero and their party can't just set up camp in the wilderness; the only place where you can get a good night's rest is at an inn, which of course costs money. The cost almost always depends on how far has the player advanced along the plot (or the character's level, in some cases). This can go to ridiculous extremes, such as \"inns\" in the middle of dungeons, to avoid getting in tents.\n\nA form of Resting Recovery, where additional restrictions are placed on where you can use that mechanic. Well on its way to being a Dead Horse Trope, as recent RPGs tend to offer characters more options to deal with resource shortage and often have faster-paced plots where taking off days at a time wouldn't be appropriate for the hero. Back in the day, however, it used to be a commonly used pacing mechanism, forcing the party to level up and get gear until they can survive a lengthy sequence between being able to recover. This mechanic can be used without involving inns or rest time at all, if the game has save points which trigger the same effect instantaneously.\n\nSee also the multiple exceptions below;", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ThereAreNoTents", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/QuestForGloryI", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/QuestForGloryIII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Phoenotopia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/KingdomHearts", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PaperMarioTheThousandYearDoor", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PaperMario", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TalesOfSymphonia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TalesOfPhantasia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TalesOfEternia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TalesOfVesperia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/FinalFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasyXI", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasyX", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ChronoTrigger", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ShadowHearts", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/BreathOfFireIII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/BreathOfFireII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ValkyrieProfile", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/GrandiaII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/SuperMarioRPG", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/SkiesOfArcadia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Opoona", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/EtrianOdyssey", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ExaPico", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DragonQuest", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DragonsDogma", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/STALKER", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/KingdomOfLoathing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Runescape", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/LegacyOfTheWizard", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/RuneFactory", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/RuneFactory3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/OgreBattle64", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/NeverwinterNights2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/UltimaIV", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/UltimaV", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/TheElderScrolls", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TheElderScrollsIIIMorrowind", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TheElderScrollsIVOblivion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TheElderScrollsVSkyrim", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/GoldBox", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Fallout", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Fallout1", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Fallout3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FalloutNewVegas", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ArcanumOfSteamworksAndMagickObscura", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/BaldursGate", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DragonAgeOrigins", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Wasteland", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MountAn